INSERT INTO `maps` VALUES ('AndersonsCounterattack','Anderson\'s Counterattack','SouthMountain','With but a few hours of daylight left the 9th and 89th New York along with Clark\'s Battery take up a defensive position on the northern side of Fox\'s Gap, defended by Garland\'s, now broken, Brigade earlier in the day. CSA Gen. G.B. Anderson, arriving with badly needed reinforcements to the remnants of the Confederate force, targets Clark\'s Battery and the two New York regiments for his counterattack. ','September 14th - 18:00 Fox\'s Gap','USA',115,127,200,'maps\\AndersonsCounterattack_skirmish.png','maps\\AndersonsCounterattack_spawn.png','maps\\AndersonsCounterattack_loading.png',3,'Colonel George B. Anderson\'s brigade had arrived late in the day after several hours of marching and conflicting orders until they reached the wooded mountains to the south of Fox\'s Gap.<br>Anderson\'s brigade was able to approach the flank of the 9th New Hampshire and capture the almost undefended Clark\'s battery, but his scouts missed the approach of Fairchild\'s brigade of New Yorkers.<br>So when the 2nd, 4th, and 13th North Carolina regiments advanced to take the Union guns for themselves, they were met by a devastating volley by both the 9th and 89th New York<br>as well as double canister sent by Clark\'s battery, Anderson\'s command could only scamper back up the hill in defeat as they left their dead and wounded lying on the mountainside.<br>The IX Corps continued to consolidate their position and control over Fox\'s Gap after having routed Garland, Drayton, and Anderson\'s brigades. The commander of the IX Corps,<br>General Jesse Reno, had been born originally in Wheeling, Virginia and grew to be a military man in the same West Point class as many prominent Civil War figures, including &quot;Stonewall&quot; Jackson,<br>George McClellan, George Pickett, and A.P. Hill. Reno had rode up to the Gap to check on his troops and congratulate them on their hard-fought victory, as well as to scout for the enemy positions.<br>As he rode upon his horse, he spotted movement in the trees to the north of Wise\'s cabin on the other side of several open fields,<br>and ordered the dual 51st regiments of New Yorkers and Pennsylvanians to investigate, before the fire of muskets lit up the scene...','Skirmish'),('BloodyLane','Bloody Lane','Antietam','A sunken road often used by farmers becomes a natural fort against a Union onslaught of Rebel lines as Union General French pushes forward with his 3rd Division and becomes engaged with elements of Confederate General D.H. Hill\'s Division entrenched in the road.','September 17th - 09:00','CSA',137,90,196,'maps\\BloodyLane_skirmish.png','maps\\BloodyLane_spawn.png','maps\\BloodyLane_loading.png',6,'As morning turned to afternoon, a sunken farming lane southeast of Dunker Church, which served local farmers to get their grain to the various mills along Antietam Creek,<br>also equally served as an already-dug trench line for the ragged Confederate infantry that made up the entire center of Lee\'s overstretched lines.<br>Despite inflicting terrible losses on several brigades of green Union troops, the Confederates inevitably broke and ran to the thin reserves<br>holding at General Longstreet\'s headquarters at the Piper Farm, where Longstreet and his staff themselves were forced to man a cannon to cover their retreat and attempt to hold the line.<br>The exhausted Union forces weren\'t able to push their advantage against the weakened center, as the battle instead shifted further west towards Dunker Church.<br>Still more troops clad in blue were streaming across Antietam Creek at various bridges and fords,<br>several points of which were hotly contested as they attempted the crossing.<br>This included the Middle Bridge, where the 4th PA Cavalry and several regular regiments of the US Army were grouped together and pushing directly west towards Sharpsburg,<br>though it was at the cost of lives such as Colonel Childs who was gutted by a cannonball, likely from one of H.P. Jones\' guns.','Skirmish'),('BolivarHeightsCamp','Bolivar Heights Camp','HarpersFerry','The Bolivar Heights was an important and strategic position for Union forces during their garrison of the town, the ridge also serving as a partial campsite to the 15,000 stationed in the beautiful valley. In this fictitious scenario, Confederate forces have breached the hastily-made defences, while Union forces desperately try to muster a counterattack.','September 15th - 09:00','USA',100,124,218,'maps\\BolivarHeightsCamp_skirmish.png','maps\\BolivarHeightsCamp_spawn.png','maps\\BolivarHeightsCamp_loading.png',5,'The town of Bolivar to the east of Harper\'s Ferry was heavily surrounded by open space, which was then capitalized on by the Union Army for the many tents needed to house all of the<br>garrisoning troops, as well as the trenches and embankments necessary to defend the upper section of the peninsula. An enterprising crew of artillery set up on the Bolivar Heights could<br>have an almost unobstructed means of bombarding the lower town, and so its retention would be vital to trying to keep the area. As such, the garrison was in easy distance of the defensive<br>works when General Jackson arrived from the direction of Shepherdstown to the north. The mostly New Yorker regiments, of which all were brand new regiments that hadn\'t seen battle before,<br>were tasked with holding the piled earth and trenches against the oncoming grey tide.<br>It was early in the morning that the shells from the Confederate artillery began to rain down on the defenders on Bolivar Heights and in the towns of Bolivar and Harper\'s Ferry.<br>General Jackson had gone so far as to say to General McLaws that he should “let the work be done thoroughly” and to “demolish the place.” Lieutenant James Clark of the 115th New York,<br>who were placed in the middle of the line defending Bolivar Heights, said of the bombardment that “at first their missiles of death fell far short of our camp; but each succeeding shell came nearer and nearer,<br>until the earth was plowed up at our feet, and our tents torn to tatters.” The troops dived for cover in what valleys and leeways they could find, but A.P. Hill\'s Walker\'s battery coming into position ended that last refuge as well.','Skirmish'),('BolivarHeightsRedoubt','Bolivar Heights Redoubt','HarpersFerry','The Bolivar Heights was an important and strategic position for Union forces during their garrison of the town, the ridge also serving as a partial campsite to the 15,000 stationed in the beautiful valley. In this fictitious scenario, Confederate forces are attacking the artillery redoubt of the entrenched Union forces.','September 15th - 10:00','USA',100,134,224,'maps\\BolivarHeightsRedoubt_skirmish.png','maps\\BolivarHeightsRedoubt_spawn.png','maps\\BolivarHeightsRedoubt_loading.png',8,'Bolivar Heights was a major ridgeline which helped separate the peninsula from the mainland of Virginia, and was also a major defensive impediment to the rebel army trying to take the town.<br>It saw early action in the war from a small skirmish that occured on the two-year anniversary of the John Brown raid, and again was threatened by General Jackson during the<br>Valley campaign in May of 1862. He nearly was able to capture the town were it not for the staunch defense of General Rufus Saxton in hastily set up embankments.<br>These paltry defenses were once again used and added to by Colonel Miles several months later, particularly with the creation of an artillery redoubt on the southern end of the heights that overlooked the Chambers Farm and Charlestown Pike.<br>Unfortunately for Colonel Miles, he did not share the success of his predecessor in defending the town when Jackson returned. The 32nd Ohio, 9th Vermont, and 125th New York<br>were all that could be brought to bear to counter the threat of A.P. Hill\'s Light Division, which was then marching up to flank from the south. Even with the help of the 87th Ohio already guarding the railroad,<br>they were little match for the entire division they were facing, and were instead pushed back up the slope in a fighting retreat.<br>It was only thanks to the call for surrender that they were able to avoid total annihilation.','Skirmish'),('BurnsideBridge','Burnside Bridge','Antietam','After several hours of preparation, Union General Burnside is ready to advance the IX Corps against Confederate General Toombs\' Brigade of skirmishers whom, while being vastly outnumbered, holds the heights overlooking the Lower Bridge crossing Antietam Creek.','September 17th - 11:30','CSA',137,88,264,'maps\\BurnsideBridge_skirmish.png','maps\\BurnsideBridge_spawn.png','maps\\BurnsideBridge_loading.png',12,'After many hours of fighting, the tenacious Georgian defenders that had dug in on the hillside overlooking the old Rohrbach bridge<br>had managed to almost hold out with only a fraction of the numbers sent against them. But it was the twin regiments of the 51st NY and 51st PA that finally managed to push across.<br>As reports came to General Toombs of Union forces from Rodman\'s Division also crossing at Snavely\'s Ford to the southwest, Toombs had to make a galling decision lest he be overrun.<br>The Confederates finally were forced back towards Sharpsburg, though it would take even more precious time for General Burnside to get his forces across the Antietam.<br>As men and guns funneled across the bridge, farther north the battlefield would briefly heat up once again, as General Greene<br>with his battered division of blue-coats became uneasy as no reinforcements arrived to help hold his advanced position west of Dunker Church.<br>His unease became justified as a horde of screaming Confederates pushed him and his men out of the woods and back across the open fields to the east.<br>While most of the Confederate forces preferred to stay under the protective cover of the treeline rather than face the many Federal guns shooting at them,<br>two regiments under the inexperienced Colonel Cooke advanced almost to the charred doorstep of the Mumma farmhouse once again...','Skirmish'),('ColquittsDefence','Colquitt\'s Defence','SouthMountain','Positioned behind a stonewall at the base of Turner\'s Gap and on the fenced-in Dahlgren Road running above the gap, overlooking the National Road headed into Turner\'s Gap, CSA Colonel Colquitt\'s brigade readies itself for the attack it knows is coming after having witnessed Union Gen. Hatch\'s attack on Garnett to the left of Colquitt\'s brigade an hour earlier. On the National Road in front of them, Union Gen. Gibbon\'s brigade begins its slow but steady push with an iron-like determination.','September 14th - 19:00 Turner\'s Gap','CSA',145,115,242,'maps\\ColquittsDefence_skirmish.png','maps\\ColquittsDefence_spawn.png','maps\\ColquittsDefence_loading.png',5,'Despite the stone walls, cliff faces, heavy woodland, and cannon fire which pelted the troops that General McClellan would call the &quot;Iron Brigade&quot;, the men of Gibbons\' brigade<br>would once again prove their mettle as they gradually pushed forward under the late afternoon sun. The 6th and 7th Wisconsin began to leapfrog over each other as one would lie down and reload<br>as the other would volley fire into the woods to their north and advance. They repeated this even as the prevailing light slowly darkened the area, plodding closer and closer towards the<br>bright flashes of light from enemy musket fire, until nine o\'clock when the darkness prevented their moving any closer.<br>Bayonets were fixed and sentinels posted for any possible rebel counterattack that might occur during the night, but none would arrive. General Lee had instead sent the general call for<br>retreat, and the Confederate army quietly returned to Boonsboro, and then across the Antietam to the town of Sharpsburg. There they would find what rest they could as the Federals<br>awakened and cautiously approached Turner\'s Gap, only to find it vacated. By September 16th, General McClellan and the Army of the Potomac reached the Antietam Creek as well and<br>prepared for the battle to come. The casualties and trouble they had gone through at South Mountain would soon pale in comparison to the fighting on the 17th. It would prove to be the single bloodiest day of the American Civil War...','Skirmish'),('CookesCountercharge','Cooke\'s Countercharge','Antietam','After several hours with no reinforcements, Union General Greene is forced to withdraw from his salient in the West Woods. Confederate Colonel Cooke orders a countercharge towards Mumma Farm in response to the fleeing Federals.','September 17th - 12:00','USA',100,137,188,'maps\\CookesCountercharge_skirmish.png','maps\\CookesCountercharge_spawn.png','maps\\CookesCountercharge_loading.png',13,'Seeing a possible advantage, Colonel Cooke had his men rise up from behind the fence line they had been sheltering at, and advanced<br>into the open towards the Mumma farm with the expectation that the other regiments positioned in the West Woods would push with them.<br>Instead, the two regiments went forward alone to face the entire Union VI Corps. However, they managed to surprise and capture a<br>large number of Yankees in their wild onrush as the other Union regiments fell back past the orchard behind the smoldering Mumma farmhouse.<br>This meant the Union regiments near the Sunken Lane were then in danger of being flanked from behind.<br>Yet as these events occurred, more fighting also occurred farther south, as General Burnside attempted to consolidate his position<br>on the other side of the Antietam Creek. The IX Corps were forced to clamber up the steep hillside that had been pockmarked with various foxholes<br>and fighting pits before reaching the summit, where the Otto and Sherrick farms stood. There the Federals skirmished with a patchwork of small Rebel<br>regiments that attempted to hold back this latest threat, one that could possibly cut the entire army off from their only avenue of escape...','Skirmish'),('CornCrib','Corn Crib','DrillCamp','','',NULL,100,100,NULL,NULL,NULL,'maps\\CornCrib_loading.png',0,NULL,'Conquest'),('CoxsPush','Cox\'s Push','SouthMountain','As the 30th and 12th Ohio attack the left flank of Garland\'s Brigade, Union Division Commander Jacob Cox pushes forward the 36th and 23rd Ohio to engage the Confederate 5th North Carolina as well as the 23rd North Carolina, having just reinforced the stretched out and besieged Confederate line. Between the two lines is Fox\'s Gap, a windswept, valley-like gap covered in stonewalls, fencing in the numerous fields covering the area.','September 14th - 11:00 Fox\'s Gap','CSA',127,115,200,'maps\\CoxsPush_skirmish.png','maps\\CoxsPush_spawn.png','maps\\CoxsPush_loading.png',1,'The 5th North Carolina were easily cut down in their exposed advanced position in an open field, and all along the line the Ohio regiments began to charge directly into the sparse remaining<br>defenders along the Wood Road, scattering and disintegrating most of the Confederate regiments. The 5th Virginia Cavalry and the two guns of Pelham\'s Battery retreated into the woods to get away<br>from the bayonets and enraged Ohioans who screamed in a murderous rampage behind them. The only remaining regiment of Garland\'s original command was the 13th North Carolina, which with<br>the help of Bondurant\'s battery as well as the 2nd and 4th North Carolinians from G. B. Anderson\'s command, desperately held off the Union troops at the Wise cabin, using the stone wall around<br>Wise\'s garden as their own Alamo against the blue tide. They too would fall and retreat from the battlefield with Fox\'s Gap firmly under Union control.<br>Farther northwest on the other side of the National Road - which was one of the oldest infrastructure projects completed by the Federal Government fifty years prior - was<br>Hooker\'s I Corps, and in particular General John Hatch\'s Division. Their attack would attempt to outflank the sparse defenders at Turner\'s Gap by moving farther north via the Frostown Road,<br>allowing them to avoid most of the Confederate firepower positioned in a crossfire against any that might attempt to push directly against Turner\'s Gap via the National Road. If successful,<br>McClellan could potentially pincer D.H. Hill\'s lone Division from two sides, and even cut off his escape back to Boonsboro...','Skirmish'),('Downtown','Downtown','HarpersFerry','In this fictitious scenario, the Confederates have breached Camp Hill, and are now assaulting the downtown area of Harper\'s Ferry where the last defenders doggedly try to hold out against them.','September 15th - 10:00','USA',100,124,152,'maps\\Downtown_skirmish.png','maps\\Downtown_spawn.png','maps\\Downtown_loading.png',2,'The downtown section of Harper\'s Ferry included many of the important businesses at ‘the Point,\' where the peninsula ends. The downtown also featured the most prominent industry<br>of the town since its purchase by the US Government under President Washington in 1796; The Harper\'s Ferry Armory - which was second only to the Springfield Armory in Massachusetts.<br>The Baltimore &amp; Ohio Railroad also crossed the Potomac at Harper\'s Ferry, with the first bridge having been completed in 1836. Over the course of the Civil War, however,<br>many businesses would be obliterated by the conflict, not to mention the destruction of both the B&amp;O bridge and the Shenandoah Bridge that had been used by lumbermen to supply fuel for the Armory.<br>Of prominent interest was the infamous John Brown\'s Fort, which had been the Armory\'s firehouse prior to the fateful night in October of 1859 that led to then-Brevet Colonel Robert E. Lee<br>being tasked by President Buchanan with quelling Brown\'s nascent uprising. Following Brown\'s refusal to surrender, it took only three minutes for Lee and his contingent of local soldiers and<br>marines to storm the firehouse and capture Brown and his surviving insurrectionists. Prior to the Siege, many Union and Confederate soldiers carved out bricks from the structure as souvenirs,<br>though before the siege it had been repaired and used as a storehouse and quartermaster building. It was also the only building to survive the two burnings of the Armory.','Skirmish'),('DrillCampCSA','Drill Camp CSA','HarpersFerry','Having crossed the Potomac earlier in the week, Confederate forces have carved out space among the ample farmland of central Maryland for a regiment-sized encampment during the Maryland Campaign of 1862. ','September, 1862',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'maps\\DrillCampCSA_skirmish.png','maps\\DrillCampCSA_spawn.png','maps\\DrillCampCSA_loading.png',1,NULL,'DrillCamp'),('DrillCampUSA','Drill Camp USA','HarpersFerry','Nestled in the lush and gently rolling hills of central Maryland, a regiment-sized camp has been set up among various farmsteads in 1862. ','September, 1862',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'maps\\DrillCampUSA_skirmish.png','maps\\DrillCampUSA_spawn.png','maps\\DrillCampUSA_loading.png',0,NULL,'DrillCamp'),('DunkerChurch','Dunker Church','Antietam','Union General Greene pushes his Division towards the rebel-held whitewashed church on the outskirts of the West Woods from the direction of the burning Mumma Farm. The church is a focal point of several Union attacks as it sits elevated on a small plateau. ','September 17th - 10:30','CSA',137,90,244,'maps\\DunkerChurch_skirmish.png','maps\\DunkerChurch_spawn.png','maps\\DunkerChurch_loading.png',11,'The Dunkers were but one subset of the many Protestant offshoots which resulted from the Reformation, named after their full ‘dunking\' of a person during a baptism.<br>Many of the adherents had fled to the United States in the decade following their founding in 1708, and in 1851 the Mumma family had donated a portion of their land for the church to be built upon.<br>Its whitewashed walls would serve as an easy landmark for commanders to guide to as the tide of blue finally marched past it and into the woods beyond.<br>A gargantuan amount of casualties would be gathered here as the church was used as an aid station, and a truce would be called on the 18th to gather the wounded and bury the many dead.<br>Greene\'s Division managed to make it halfway through the West Woods before their momentum dried up. Instead they set up a defensive salient<br>against any possible counterattack, however the next main action to arrive would be farther south, at the lower bridge over the Antietam Creek.<br>General Burnside in command of the IX Corps had taken the majority of the day to set up his attack, and at 10 o\'clock finally received the orders from General McClellan to advance.<br>Guarding the bridge were two batteries and the Georgians under General Robert Toombs. They were all that stood between Sharpsburg<br>and the entire Union IX Corps, which would send wave after wave of regiments to attack the bottleneck at the bridge.','Skirmish'),('EastWoods','East Woods','Antietam','As Confederate General Hood attempts to push the advancing Union General Hooker\'s I Corps back into the Cornfield, some of his forces also push against the Union holding in the East Woods directly adjacent to Miller\'s Cornfield.  ','September 17th - 07:20','USA',100,124,218,'maps\\EastWoods_skirmish.png','maps\\EastWoods_spawn.png','maps\\EastWoods_loading.png',4,'Approximately twenty minutes after beginning their push from the West Woods,<br>most of Law\'s rebel brigade were able to get through the woods with only the paltry defense lent by the 10th Maine to stop them.<br>However, down the Smoketown Road came General Mansfield who rode at the head of over 8,000 men of the 12th Corps,<br>though the General would be shot in the chest by rebel sharpshooters as he surveyed the situation.<br>Yet his Corps would continue to advance inexorably southward,<br>also with the Church and the bellowing rebel cannons in front of it as their target, while shattering Law\'s rebel lines before them.<br>Farther to the northwest, for two hours rebel gunners positioned on Nicodemus Hill had been able to bombard the flanks of the Yankee forces below them,<br>but if General Hooker had decided to silence their guns once and for all, then an attack would likely have been launched from the Miller farm by the men of Doubleday\'s division,<br>as Confederate elements of both infantry and Jackson\'s brash cavalry attempt to defend their guns from the Union advance...','Skirmish'),('EastWoodsSkirmish','East Woods Skirmish','Antietam','During the late afternoon of September 16th, General Hooker takes his Corps across Antietam creek at the upper bridge in order to locate the rebel flank. In the waning light, the 42nd PA and 3rd PA reserves are sent out in a skirmish formation to probe the East Woods for rebels.','September 16th - 20:00','CSA',137,115,204,'maps\\EastWoodsSkirmish_skirmish.png','maps\\EastWoodsSkirmish_spawn.png','maps\\EastWoodsSkirmish_loading.png',0,'After their victory at South Mountain, Union General McClellan with his Army of the Potomac was close on the heels of Confederate Generals Longstreet and Hill as they quickly retreated across Antietam Creek to set up a defensive line.<br>After Union General Hooker crossed with the 1st Corps, it was up to two regiments of Pennsylvanians to find and probe Lee\'s vulnerable left flank.<br>When darkness finally ended the brief skirmish, Union troops had pushed the Confederate forces away from the East Woods, but both armies could barely sleep as skirmishing fire continued throughout the night.<br>As the next morning dawned, however, the Confederate and Union troops stirred from their slumber for the action to come.<br>The unending skirmish fire erupted further into proper battle as lines of infantry and batteries of artillery added to the cacophony.<br>Just west of the East Woods lies the cornfield owned by the Miller family, and by 6:00 on the morning of the 17th,<br>the veteran troops of the Union Iron Brigade would advance from the North Woods and through the cornfield into the open fields to their south, right into a withering fire...','Skirmish'),('Farmland','Farmland','Antietam','','',NULL,100,100,NULL,NULL,NULL,'maps\\Farmland_loading.png',3,NULL,'Conquest'),('ForestStream','Forest Stream','Antietam','','',NULL,100,100,NULL,NULL,NULL,'maps\\ForestStream_loading.png',1,NULL,'Conquest'),('FramingFencelines','Framing Fencelines','Antietam','','',NULL,100,100,NULL,NULL,NULL,'maps\\FramingFencelines_loading.png',2,NULL,'Conquest'),('GarlandsStand','Garland\'s Stand','SouthMountain','CSA Brig. General Samuel Garland having been ordered by Maj. Gen. D.H. Hill to defend Fox\'s Gap and its road - directly exposing the wagon trains of the Confederate army should it fall, is now deploying his brigade next to the Wise Farm. To his immediate front Union Colonel Scammon\'s brigade consisting of the 30th and 12th Ohio is advancing and engaging with the 13th and 20th North Carolina while the 23rd Ohio is putting pressure on his far too drawn-out line\'s right flank.','September 14th - 10:00 close to Fox\'s Gap','CSA',137,115,256,'maps\\GarlandsStand_skirmish.png','maps\\GarlandsStand_spawn.png','maps\\GarlandsStand_loading.png',0,'As Lee entered Maryland, he envisioned a state ready to welcome his Army with open arms, and even to threaten the heartland of the North just as the Federals had repeatedly done<br>for the previous year in Virginia and the Carolinas. However, in the intricate dance set between Generals McClellan and Lee, the former could hardly believe his luck in finding the infamous<br>Special Order 191. The Union general\'s uncharacteristic aggressiveness then caught General Lee on the back foot, and he found the closest defensive position for his disjointed command:<br>the passes of South Mountain. On September 14th, General Samuel Garland of D.H. Hill\'s Division would rush southwest from Turner\'s Gap,<br>tasked with finding defensive positions at Fox\'s Gap and facing off with the first elements of General Jacob Cox\' division that approached the pass.<br>Garland\'s North Carolinians would hold against the Ohioan regiments for a small while, though at the cost of General Garland\'s life. Two James rifles of the 1st Battery of Ohio Light<br>Artillery had run their guns up so close to the enemy that the artillerymen were butchered as they tried to man the guns, but the 30th Ohio were able to flank around the stone fence the<br>North Carolinians were firing from, and raked their lines with heavy fire as they fell in droves. The far right flank of the Confederate lines were held by the 5th Virginia Cavalry, two 3-inch<br>Ordnance Rifles of Pelham\'s Battery, and the 5th North Carolina Infantry. They were all that stood at Fox\'s Gap itself against a fresh set of Union troops under Colonel George Crook,<br>which now marched up the Loop Road and across the fields towards the beleaguered defenders...','Skirmish'),('HagerstownTurnpike','Hagerstown Turnpike','Antietam','Upon leaving Miller\'s Cornfield, the Union attacks the Confederates who are defending the Hagerstown Turnpike, a road running next to the cornfield. Its fenced in sides and the road itself functions as a clear line between Jackson\'s forces in the West Woods and Hooker\'s south of the cornfield.','September 17th - 06:30','CSA',124,100,130,'maps\\HagerstownTurnpike_skirmish.png','maps\\HagerstownTurnpike_spawn.png','maps\\HagerstownTurnpike_loading.png',2,'Following their successful push southward from the Cornfield, Union forces looked to secure Hagerstown Turnpike as well while they continued towards Dunker Church.<br>Facing them were two Confederate brigades under Generals Starke and Taliaterro, the former of which included the fierce Louisiana Tigers.<br>The Union\'s Iron Brigade would bash against their savage defense before the rebels were forced to retreat back to the West Woods to their southwest.<br>However, unbeknownst to the Federal troops, even more Confederate forces were waiting under the shadowed boughs of the West Woods.<br>The hungry and tired Texans, Georgians, and South Carolinians of Wofford\'s Brigade, who had set up some breakfast fires in the hope of a quick meal before battle,<br>were instead roused by the orders of their officers back into their battle lines.<br>Soon they would march northward to the sounds of gunfire and screaming carnage on the other side of the chilly,<br>shaded treeline, back towards a lonely cornfield that still had more death in store for its tilled ground.','Skirmish'),('HarpersFerryUSA','Harpers Ferry USA',NULL,'Situated in the beautiful Shenandoah Valley, Bolivar Heights is one of three the commands an overlook of the town of Harper\'s Ferry below. Camp Hill and the Bolivar Heights were taken over by those garrisoning this strategically important confluence of rail and water.','September, 1862',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'maps\\HarpersFerryUSA_skirmish.png','maps\\HarpersFerryUSA_spawn.png','maps\\HarpersFerryUSA_loading.png',0,NULL,NULL),('HarpersGraveyard','Harpers Graveyard','HarpersFerry','In this fictitious scenario, following the taking of Bolivar Heights, the Confederates are launching an assault on the last holdouts of the garrison via the historic Harper\'s Graveyard.','September 15th - 14:30','USA',115,124,134,'maps\\HarpersGraveyard_skirmish.png','maps\\HarpersGraveyard_spawn.png','maps\\HarpersGraveyard_loading.png',7,'When Robert Harper passed away in 1782, he was laid to rest on the hill overlooking the town he had spent the last few decades developing, and by 1803 the area around his burial plot<br>was officially demarcated as the town cemetery at the demand of Robert\'s son, William. John Hall, who would become the US Armory\'s first Superintendent, would occupy the property just<br>west of the cemetery, and with the government\'s help made additions and improvements to the original cottage and outbuildings. In 1848, Superintendent John Symington redesigned the road<br>and armory housing layout for Camp Hill, including the demolition of the Hall cottage to make way for the new Paymaster\'s Quarters. With the burning of the armory itself,<br>many of the government buildings on Camp Hill were overtaken as officer\'s quarters for the local garrison alongside the tent city which had sprung up on the hillsides.<br>Like many graveyards of the 19th century, the Harper Graveyard remained a peaceful and quiet getaway from the bustle of town and its several industries for the local citizens.<br>Many of the most prominent townsfolk and veterans of many wars were buried and remembered there, including several veterans from the Revolutionary War through to the Mexican-American War.<br>General Miles might have used that quietude as he considered the troops put in his care to defend against half of the Confederate army, saying of their quality that many had “never had a<br>gun in their hands until the boxes were opened and the muskets issued to them yesterday.” That in part was perhaps a large factor in his decisions to come....','Skirmish'),('HatchsAttack','Hatch\'s Attack','SouthMountain','In an effort to secure the southern part of South Mountain itself and thus open up the flank of Confederate Major General D.H. Hill situated at the strong defensive positions at Mountain House and on the Dahlgren Road at Turner\'s Gap, Union Brig. Gen. John Hatch\'s 3500-man division pushes onwards and upwards through some of the most difficult and rocky terrain of the battlefield. On top of the crest CSA General Garnett\'s 400-man division is rushing forwards to safeguard the flank of the mountain gap.','September 14th - 18:30 close to Turner\'s Gap','CSA',127,115,218,'maps\\HatchsAttack_skirmish.png','maps\\HatchsAttack_spawn.png','maps\\HatchsAttack_loading.png',2,'General John Porter Hatch had done well as a cavalry brigade commander until the Valley Campaign, where after two failed cavalry raids he was transferred to commanding the<br>Corps\' 1st Division of infantry. Hatch\'s men had advanced directly across fields of corn and woodlands before reaching the Frostown Road near the Daniel Rent farm. Farther up the hill,<br>the Virginians under General Garnett awaited the Federals arrival, and neither side could see the other until they were almost upon each other.<br>Despite the strong Confederate position behind fence lines and woodland, the number of Union regiments allowed them to outflank and outmatch their gray counterparts,<br>even despite General Hatch being wounded by a shot in the leg early in the fight. His division would even manage to almost reach the summit of the mountain north of Turner\'s Gap.<br>Farther south at Fox\'s Gap, Confederate reinforcements were finally arriving, as were the remaining elements of the Union IX Corps, which had mistakenly headed towards Turner\'s Gap<br>before being turned around by General Burnside back to Fox\'s Gap. By 5:00, after several hours of deadly and accurate fire from Bondurant\'s rebel guns,<br>four new brigades of Confederates had finally arrived down the Old Sharpsburg Road to push back the Union IX Corps which gathered in strength below them.<br>One failed offensive by General Drayton sent his men scurrying back to the protection of the stone walls, before they too collapsed from the Union onslaught,<br>but another brigade of North Carolinians would soon have something to say...','Skirmish'),('HighStreet','High Street','HarpersFerry','In this fictitious scenario, the Union garrison under General Miles attempt to defend the north side of Camp Hill against Confederate assaults after their taking of the Bolivar Heights. ','September 15th - 11:00','USA',110,124,142,'maps\\HighStreet_skirmish.png','maps\\HighStreet_spawn.png','maps\\HighStreet_loading.png',4,'High Street was one of the main roads leading from the downtown area up to Camp Hill and the town of Bolivar, transitioning into Washington Street after passing Clay Street.<br>Many residences and shops were found along this street for the townsfolk, and the road also passes by the beginning of the famous stone staircase, which had been hand carved out of the shale by<br>parishioners of both the St. John and St. Paul churches in the 1820s. The staircase had been expanded to reach the equally famous Jefferson Rock which overlooks the beautiful river valley,<br>and was the spot from which Thomas Jefferson and his daughter gazed at the natural beauty of the area in 1783.<br>The staircase also passes the location of Robert Harper\'s own residence which was completed in 1782, though he never had the chance to live there himself.<br>The beginning of High Street was opposite Arsenal Square, a collection of warehouses where many of the finished products from the Armory were stored and closely guarded from<br>folks such as John Brown, who would intend to use the stock for their ill-intended pursuits. The Arsenal stores were also used by more illustrious passers-by, such as Meriwether Lewis in 1803,<br>just a year after the manufactory officially opened. He was able to acquire a number of guns, equipment, and trade items from the twenty-five armorers then working at the factory,<br>as well as help with the creation of his collapsible iron-framed canoe he had designed for the trip west. While the other items worked perfectly, Lewis was mortified when his collapsible canoe wasn\'t able to stay afloat two years later.&#10;','Skirmish'),('HillsCounterattack','Hill\'s Counterattack','Antietam','Confederate General Hill arrives from Harper\'s Ferry late in the day with his Light Division partially wearing captured Federal uniforms. The Division smashes into the flank of the advancing Burnside\'s Corps which has been delayed heavily earlier in the day at the Lower Bridge.','September 17th - 17:00','USA',115,124,178,'maps\\HillsCounterattack_skirmish.png','maps\\HillsCounterattack_spawn.png','maps\\HillsCounterattack_loading.png',17,'At close to five in the afternoon, the signal station at Elk Mountain sent a dire warning to the signalmen located at General Burnside\'s headquarters at the Rohrbach Farm to &quot;look well on his left&quot;<br>for A.P Hill\'s Light Division had arrived to reinforce the Confederate right. Where the IX Corps had managed to almost reach the outskirts of Sharpsburg,<br>they were instead forced back to the ridgeline overlooking Antietam Creek due to the sudden onslaught. While some preparation had been made, the sheer force of Carolinian Infantry and batteries of artillery<br>were too much to bear for the tired Union forces, and with their retreat it was the end of the battle as the evening light closed on the bloodiest single day of the war.<br>Over the course of a few hours, almost 23,000 men would be dead, wounded, or missing from the Battle of Antietam. Following a brief truce to collect the wounded and bury the dead on the 18th,<br>General McClellan expected further battle to take place, only for General Lee to leave his campfires burnings overnight as his army slipped away to cross the Potomac at Shepherdstown.<br>While some elements sent to find the Army of Northern Virginia would eventually engage his vanguard on the 19th and 20th there, Lee was still able to retreat back into Confederate territory.<br>Antietam was proclaimed a Union victory, and enough of one that President Lincoln could announce plans that for all those living in bondage in the rebellious states, &quot;henceforward shall be free.&quot;<br>Yet the war would continue on for another grueling three years, and this hard-fought battlefield - its streams, hillocks, and woods - would not be the last.','Skirmish'),('Hilltop','Hilltop','SouthMountain','','',NULL,100,100,NULL,NULL,NULL,'maps\\Hilltop_loading.png',3,NULL,'Conquest'),('HookersPush','Hooker\'s Push','Antietam','In the early fog of dawn, Union General Joseph Hooker pushes southwards with his I Corps, starting from the edge of North Woods, past the R. Miller Farm and through the Miller Cornfield only to be engaged south of it by defending Confederate General Ewell\'s Division at about 7 AM.','September 17th - 06:00','CSA',124,100,390,'maps\\HookersPush_skirmish.png','maps\\HookersPush_spawn.png','maps\\HookersPush_loading.png',1,'In the early morning hours of September 17th, various brigades of Union troops, including the recently famous Iron Brigade,<br>would march from the North Woods and through the Miller family cornfield under heavy fire from rebel guns on Nicodemus Hill,<br>and push the Confederate lines back from the open field beyond.<br>However, every inch of ground was hotly contested, and Ewell\'s Division of Confederates made sure<br>the Federals paid for every rock and blade of grass they took over as the rebels retreated to the south and east across the Hagerstown Pike.<br>The Federals would continue their drive towards the whitewashed Dunker Church which became Hooker\'s goal for the Union 1st Corps to reach.<br>But where General Hooker believed he was flanking the entire Confederate left, he was instead facing the staunch defense of three divisions<br>who awaited the Federal\'s arrival with grim determination.<br>On the Union side, Rickett\'s, Meade\'s, and Doubleday\'s Division would march over 600 yards while slogging through heavy rebel fire<br>to try and reach the Church, but they would need to clear out the defenders along the Pike first...','Skirmish'),('LimestoneBridge','Limestone Bridge','Antietam','','',NULL,100,100,NULL,NULL,NULL,'maps\\LimestoneBridge_loading.png',4,NULL,'Conquest'),('LogCabin','Log Cabin','SouthMountain','','',NULL,100,100,NULL,NULL,NULL,'maps\\LogCabin_loading.png',0,NULL,'Conquest'),('MarylandHeights','Maryland Heights','HarpersFerry','Early on the morning of the 13th, Kershaw\'s and Barksdale\'s Brigades of Confederates attack the Maryland Heights while the 32nd Ohio and 126th New York try to guard the approach to Harper\'s Ferry.','September 13th - 09:30','USA',190,190,174,'maps\\MarylandHeights_skirmish.png','maps\\MarylandHeights_spawn.png','maps\\MarylandHeights_loading.png',0,'Maryland Heights had long overlooked the town of Harper\'s Ferry, which was once called “one of the most stupendous scenes in nature” by Thomas Jefferson as he traveled to Philadelphia in 1783.<br>The town\'s namesake, the ambitious Robert Harper, had ensured that it became an important hub of travel and industry since its founding in 1761.<br>During the Civil War, the Maryland Heights were quickly fortified with various artillery emplacements, though in 1862 these defenses were put to little use by the sparse defenders sent by Colonel Dixon Miles,<br>who commanded the Union garrison. After five hours of holding off two Confederate brigades, with the mortal wounding of Colonel Eliakim Sherrill of the 126th NY,<br>there was little holding the green regiments together to defend the heights. The Union troops would end up retreating to the town, leaving the Heights entirely to the Confederates.<br>With the taking of the Maryland Heights, the next task for the rebels was for four Parrott guns to be brought up, each of which weighed almost 1800 lbs and took two-hundred men each<br>to lug them up the steep slopes of the mountain. The naval guns that had been set up earlier in the year along the heights, including the massive 50lb Parrott and two nine inch Dahlgrens,<br>had all been spiked by the Union artillerymen as they saw the infantry retreating. General McLaws was then forced to focus his attention on General Franklin\'s VI Corps bearing down on the<br>troops he had defending Crampton\'s Gap, leaving only a single regiment to hold the Heights. They had much to thank from Colonel Miles\' reticence that the Union garrison didn\'t attempt a breakout towards them,<br>especially as the booms of cannonfire could be heard coming from the nearby South Mountain passes on the 14th.','Skirmish'),('MillersCornfield','Miller\'s Cornfield','Antietam','An hour after the early morning actions of General Hooker and his Corps near the Miller farmstead, the damaged cornfield is subjected to a new infusion of blood, this time from the men of Hood\'s division. A withering fire from several sides mean that terrible casualties are wrought.','September 17th - 07:00','USA',110,124,142,'maps\\MillersCornfield_skirmish.png','maps\\MillersCornfield_spawn.png','maps\\MillersCornfield_loading.png',3,'With a sudden and shrill explosion of devilish voices, Hood\'s Division burst from the West Woods and headed northeast,<br>rapidly pushing the Yankees back across the Hagerstown Turnpike, and then north through the Miller cornfield in a wild onrush of grey and butternut.<br>Wofford\'s Confederate brigade would almost reach the northern boundary of the cornfield in their advance,<br>but they extended too far and became flanked on three sides by artillery and infantry, which cut man and cornstalk down in equal measure in a hail of lead and smoke.<br>As the fighting occurred in the cornfields to the west, in the East Woods which partially bordered the cornfield,<br>Law\'s brigade advanced into their abandoned forward outposts from the previous night,<br>but in a turn of fate it was now they who would be matched by a furious charge by the Yankees in blue,<br>as the entire 12th Corps under the aged General Mansfield met them head on.<br>Ohioans and Pennsylvanians would once again clash with their Confederate counterparts as even more support from Garland\'s North Carolinian brigade joined the fray...','Skirmish'),('NicodemusHill','Nicodemus Hill','Antietam','Confederates are defending Jackson\'s artillery positioned on Nicodemus Hill from the Union attacking from the direction of Miller farm. The commanding viewpoint offered by Nicodemus Hill offers Washington\'s, Chew\'s, and Pelham\'s batteries devastating fire down the Union lines.','September 17th - 08:45','CSA',147,95,146,'maps\\NicodemusHill_skirmish.png','maps\\NicodemusHill_spawn.png','maps\\NicodemusHill_loading.png',5,'The Nicodemus farmstead suffered little structural damage, despite the immense amount of shells which screamed a deathly whine above it<br>from the exchanges of counter battery fire between the Confederates on Nicodemus Hill and the Union artillery<br>stationed en masse at the Joseph Poffenberger farm just above the North Woods.<br>But for the women and children which had briefly taken refuge in the Nicodemus farmhouse prior to the battle starting,<br>few wished to remain to find out if an errant shell might crash towards them instead.<br>However, during the battle General McClellan placed a higher emphasis on pushing south towards the town of Sharpsburg.<br>While the I and XII Corps were gaining ground again down the Hagerstown Pike and from the East Woods,<br>it was Sumner\'s II Corps of Lincolnites that were next to enter the fray.<br>Yet awaiting them were three understrength brigades of Confederates in an old sunken farming road,<br>which would soon become an open grave for thousands of bodies, which would be known as &quot;Bloody Lane&quot;...','Skirmish'),('Orchards','Orchards','DrillCamp','','',NULL,100,100,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,1,NULL,'Conquest'),('OttoSherrickFarm','Otto & Sherrick Farm','Antietam','The idyllic farms of the Otto and Sherrick families becomes a heavily contested area as the two forces clash. The farms are situated in close proximity to the Lower Bridge and moving towards the town of Sharpsburg dictates passing their grounds.','September 17th - 12:30','CSA',137,90,136,'maps\\OttoSherrickFarm_skirmish.png','maps\\OttoSherrickFarm_spawn.png','maps\\OttoSherrickFarm_loading.png',14,'In 1831, the widow Margaret Ham sold her Mount Pleasant property in two lots, one to Joseph Sherrick and the other to John Otto, who became fellow neighbors<br>and parishioners at Dunker Church farther north. The Otto family even donated the bricks for the building of it, while Joseph Sherrick, Samuel Mumma,<br>and Daniel Miller supervised its construction. But these picturesque farms would soon be inundated by soldiers and death, as with most every scrap of food taken<br>and the farms used as hospitals once the battle had shifted past them. Thankfully, the $3000 in gold Joseph Sherrick hid in one stone wall was still there when they had the chance to return.<br>However, with the continued advancement of Cooke\'s troops towards the Mumma farm farther north, it meant the troops closer to the Sunken Lane suddenly had enemies to their rear.<br>It forced the bloodied and exhausted members of Kimball\'s Brigade to about face and move to find defensive positions along Roulette Lane near the Clipp and Roulette farms.<br>The cornfields to their new front were teeming with rebels that had already wreaked havoc among several Union regiments as they charged pell mell across the open fields<br>between Dunker Church and Mumma farm. Here the Union regiments would attempt to hold off against this last ditch effort by the Confederates as devilish cries reached their ears...','Skirmish'),('Outskirts','Outskirts','HarpersFerry','','',NULL,100,100,NULL,NULL,NULL,'maps\\Outskirts_loading.png',1,NULL,'Conquest'),('Overlook','Overlook','HarpersFerry','','',NULL,100,100,NULL,NULL,NULL,'maps\\Overlook_loading.png',2,NULL,'Conquest'),('PicketPatrol','Picket Patrol',NULL,'Eliminate enemy picket force.<br>One life per round.<br>Random team spawn points.<br>Strict formation rules.','September, 1862',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'maps\\PicketPatrol_spawn.png','maps\\PicketPatrol_loading.png',0,NULL,NULL),('PiperFarm','Piper Farm','Antietam','The 7th Maine is ordered by Colonel Irwin to push past the bodies at the Bloody Lane, the Piper Cornfield, the apple orchard and attack the Piper farm buildings themselves, which act as headquarters for Confederate Wing Commander General Longstreet. 4 Confederate brigades await them.','September 17th - 16:30','CSA',124,90,132,'maps\\PiperFarm_skirmish.png','maps\\PiperFarm_spawn.png','maps\\PiperFarm_loading.png',16,'In response to harassing sharpshooter fire coming from the apple orchard near the Piper Farm, the 7th Maine under command of Major Thomas Hyde was ordered to clear the sharpshooters out.<br>Hyde was confused by Colonel Irwin\'s orders, considering the obvious presence of a considerable number of rebels dug in around the farm just behind the orchard,<br>and the 7th Maine barely had 181 men to its roster. Despite this, they advanced and all alone, they successfully managed to clear out the sharpshooters,<br>but they were caught in a deadly crossfire that even despite the expert maneuvers by Major Hyde to help his troops avoid the worst of it,<br>would result in less than 70 managing to make it back to friendly lines. Colonel Irwin would be removed from command shortly after.<br>This last bit of fighting in the northern part of the battlefield - which had been advised more by &quot;John Barleycorn&quot; than by sensible military tactics<br>was shortly followed by one last surprise General Lee still had left to play for the battle. Far to the southwest, General A.P Hill and his Light Division had been left behind in Harpers Ferry<br>to parole the 15,000 Union prisoners taken in the siege, and by late afternoon had finally arrived to help the endangered southern flank of Lee\'s lines. His troops, then clad in part with captured Union uniforms,<br>would serve as a nasty surprise on the left flank of General Burnside\'s IX Corps as they attempted to assault Sharpsburg. It would be a bloody revelation for several New Englander regiments...','Skirmish'),('PryFord','Pry Ford','Antietam','In this alternate scenario, grey-clad soldiers hold an important point near a ford on the Antietam Creek, and are attacked by dismounted Union cavalry under Pleasanton used by Union Commander General McClellan as skirmishers probing for the enemy throughout the day of fighting.','September 17th - 09:30','CSA',124,105,208,'maps\\PryFord_skirmish.png','maps\\PryFord_spawn.png','maps\\PryFord_loading.png',7,'The idyllic Antietam Creek was an important waterway which powered a number of grist mills for the wheat and corn grown in the area.<br>It also was a natural barrier between the two armies as they met for battle.<br>Thus one of the logistical and strategic hurdles for General McClellan to consider was how to get tens of thousands of men,<br>horses, and cannon across in time to engage against the Confederates.<br>On the 16th, Rebel pickets spotted the first elements of the I Corps crossing at Pry Ford and the Upper Bridge,<br>with more moving across during the night and the next morning.<br>Of course, not all actions could be done with impunity, and some light skirmishes occurred on both days as the armies vied against each other.<br>Besides the fords and bridges, otherwise mundane structures could become important strategic buildings and defensive points,<br>as was the case with one of the grist mills owned by the Pry Family.<br>More blood would be spilt here in the fateful days during and after the battle, but this time by more friendly and caring hands.','Skirmish'),('PryGristMill','Pry Grist Mill','Antietam','In this alternate scenario, Hooker\'s forces must contend with Confederate skirmishers holding an important crossing point of the Little Antietam creek. Pry\'s Grist Mill is situated near the confluence of Little Antietam and Antietam Creek and is a major supplier of flour in the region. ','September 17th - 10:00','CSA',124,105,164,'maps\\PryGristMill_skirmish.png','maps\\PryGristMill_spawn.png','maps\\PryGristMill_loading.png',8,'The Pry Grist Mill had originally been built in 1820 by Samuel Hitt with two stories, and even diverted the main road to specifically pass by.<br>Two years after it was purchased by the Pry brothers, in 1850 a fire burned down the wooden upper story, which they replaced with brick and built even higher.<br>During the Battle of Antietam it was chosen by General McClellan\'s medical director, Major Jonathan Letterman,<br>as one of seven field hospitals as part of the new system he had devised and implemented the previous month<br>to treat the immense amount of wounded that would quickly fill the fields and forests around the mill.<br>The Pry family was hit hard by the exigencies of war, though Samuel Pry who owned the Mill was able to get by much better than his brother,<br>Philip, whose entire farm was taken over as a combination of Union headquarters, hospital, and artillery park, causing thousands of dollars in damages.<br>The quiet life that Philip and his wife Elizabeth had built along with their five children would soon be turned upside down as soldiers,<br>horses, and wagons streamed through by the thousands towards a deadly confrontation...','Skirmish'),('PryHouse','Pry House','Antietam','In this alternative scenario pockets of Confederate forces have managed to sneak by the Union line and are attacking Pry House, headquarter of commanding Union General George B. McClellan. ','September 17th - 10:00','USA',115,134,144,'maps\\PryHouse_skirmish.png','maps\\PryHouse_spawn.png','maps\\PryHouse_loading.png',9,'Philip Pry had built his farm with the help of his brother Samuel from the ground up in 1844, but twenty quiet years meant little to the army that needed to bend the land to their needs.<br>With its commanding view over much of the prospective battlefield to the west, General McClellan and his staff were quick to make use<br>of the western overlook and even the attic roof access hatch to survey the battlefield and divvy out orders.<br>The house and barn were also a convenient field hospital and headquarters of Major Letterman, the Medical Director for the Army of the Potomac.<br>His revamping of the entire medical corps - which he had conceived the month prior - would be put to the test with the immense amount of wounded that would result from the battle.<br>More yet were sure to come as Union forces headed next into the West Woods; a disjointed polygon of woodland that divided the old Mary Grove Locher land tract and the Mumma and Miller farms.<br>The Union II Corps under General Edwin Sumner had crossed over Antietam Creek and joined the fray.<br>But as they marched towards the burning Mumma Farm, Sedgwick\'s 2nd Division suddenly became isolated when General French<br>became confused on which direction to go and mistakenly took his division south, leaving Sedgwick vulnerable and alone as the trees enveloped his men, many to never return.','Skirmish'),('RailroadCut','Railroad Cut','DrillCamp','','',NULL,100,100,NULL,NULL,NULL,'maps\\RailroadCut_loading.png',2,NULL,'Conquest'),('RenosFall','Reno\'s Fall','SouthMountain','After the Confederate collapse at Fox\'s Gap earlier in the day due to the attacks by Union Maj. Gen. Reno\'s IX Corps, CSA Brig. Gen. Hood now orders his division south to relieve the battered Confederate lines in an effort to regain a foothold at the gap. To deny the Confederates the chance of doing so, the 51st New York and Pennsylvania are sent forward with the Corps commander in close proximity in order to inspire his troops and inspect the lines.','September 14th - 18:00 close to Fox\'s Gap','USA',115,127,221,'maps\\RenosFall_skirmish.png','maps\\RenosFall_spawn.png','maps\\RenosFall_loading.png',4,'General Jesse Reno at the age of 39 was mortally wounded from the incoming fire poured into the Union ranks by elements of Hood\'s Division. While return fire helped to clear out the Confederate skirmishers,<br>the damage had been done, and the fight over Fox\'s Gap that had gone for almost ten hours was finally done as daylight faded from the valley.<br>Some 12,000 men of the IX Corps had successfully taken their objective despite the 7,500 Confederates which had tried to defend against them, though Ripley\'s brigade had only managed to get lost in Pleasant Valley,<br>while Garland and Drayton\'s brigade had been scattered, destroyed, and captured. Yet the loss of their beloved commander was a harsh blow that tempered their victory against the Confederacy.<br>Slightly northeast, General McClellan was correct in his assumption that the National Road would be heavily defended, but for his other attacks to work there still had to be some threat in the center.<br>Thus late in the afternoon General Gibbons\' brigade would be sent forward with two regiments on both sides of the National Road. Facing him would be the men of Rain\'s Brigade,<br>under the command of Colonel Alfred Colquitt. Including both hardy Georgians and Alabamians, their brigade was tasked with holding the southern half of Turner\'s Gap<br>from the direction of the National Road to their east They would be witnesses to the bravery and fortitude of their Northern counterparts as they marched in ordered lines up the macadamized road towards them.','Skirmish'),('RiverCrossing','River Crossing','HarpersFerry','In this fictitious scenario, Confederates under General McLaws desperately attempt to cross the Potomac River to assault the town of Harper\'s Ferry from both sides.','September 15th - 09:30','USA',120,199,262,'maps\\RiverCrossing_skirmish.png','maps\\RiverCrossing_spawn.png','maps\\RiverCrossing_loading.png',1,'The Shenandoah and Potomac Rivers had for millions of years converged and cut through the tough quartzite and softer rocks of several Appalachian ridgelines on their quest to the sea.<br>These waters were an important factor to local commerce and industry, as the waters were used to feed canals for both boating, and for waterpower in the many factories along their banks.<br>With the burning of the pre-Civil War bridges by the Confederates in 1861, Union engineers had erected a pontoon bridge in early 1862 across the Potomac River at the base of<br>the Maryland Heights to ferry wagons and horses safely. On the 14th, the pontoons were used by the intrepid Captain Benjamin Davis and 1,200 troopers of various cavalry units to cross in<br>the middle of the night and escape the siege, and to get word to General McClellan of the town\'s plight.<br>While Davis and his cavalry detachment managed to capture Longstreet\'s artillery ammunition wagons on their way to find the Army of the Potomac, the next morning left the town<br>in an even tighter grip by Confederate forces. General McLaws had finished clearing enough of the mountain for his cannons to operate, and set up a better road for his troops and guns,<br>while General Walker had arrived on Loudon Heights south of the Shenandoah with his guns. Finally, General Jackson, in overall charge of the siege, had arrived down the Shepherdstown Road<br>from the north and positioned his forces on Schoolhouse Ridge, completing the encirclement. Even the Union officers fully realized that with the giving up of the Maryland and Loudon Heights, defeat was a mere inevitability...','Skirmish'),('RiverTown','River Town','HarpersFerry','','',NULL,100,100,NULL,NULL,NULL,'maps\\RiverTown_loading.png',0,NULL,'Conquest'),('RockySlopes','Rocky Slopes','SouthMountain','','',NULL,100,100,NULL,NULL,NULL,'maps\\RockySlopes_loading.png',2,NULL,'Conquest'),('RouletteLane','Roulette Lane','Antietam','The 3rd Arkansas and 27th North Carolina under Colonel Cooke find themselves on the flank of the Federals now in possession of the Sunken Road. The 1st Delaware and 14th Indiana are tasked with holding the rebels back at Roulette Lane.','September 17th - 12:45','USA',95,137,156,'maps\\RouletteLane_skirmish.png','maps\\RouletteLane_spawn.png','maps\\RouletteLane_loading.png',15,'The area that was the Roulette farm had originally been owned by the Miller family before the death of John Miller IV, whose widow Ann would sell it<br>to her step-sister\'s husband; a gentleman named William Roulette. This farm would soon be subject to the ebb and flow of battle as William hid in the basement<br>from the conflict that ravaged the house above him. Yet even with having the advantage of surprise, there was little that two lonesome Confederate regiments<br>could do when faced against an entire corps worth of Union combatants that surrounded them on three sides. Once again Cooke\'s command was forced to retreat as a hail of bullets followed them in their wake.<br>As Cooke and his men retreated, he was in part followed by a brigade of mainly New Yorkers, and one small battalion from Maine, all under the command of Colonel William Irwin,<br>who would on five occasions be accused of being a habitual drunkard. After a desultory and failed advance against the Confederates in the West Woods, by 4:00 PM the men of Iwin\'s brigade<br>had found what cover they could in the swales of the open ground between Dunker Church and the burned Mumma farm.<br>Yet as fire from sharpshooters and Confederate guns alike whistled and screamed over their heads, Irwin would give a command that would prove disastrous to the understrength 7th Maine...','Skirmish'),('SchoolHouseRidge','School House Ridge','HarpersFerry','During the siege of Harper\'s Ferry, General Stonewall Jackson had lined a large portion of his force along Schoolhouse Ridge, which sat opposite a valley overlooked by the Bolivar Heights, which the Union had hastily fortified. In this fictitious scenario, the Confederates attempt to make a frontal charge against the strong defenses of the Union!','September 15th - 06:30','USA',124,188,100,'maps\\SchoolHouseRidge_skirmish.png','maps\\SchoolHouseRidge_spawn.png','maps\\SchoolHouseRidge_loading.png',3,'Schoolhouse Ridge was the third furrow of elevation that occured to the west of the Harper\'s Ferry peninsula, and it was there that Stonewall Jackson arranged his three divisions<br>of Jones, Lawton and A.P. Hill. The Confederate forces were very surprised by the lack of challenge from Colonel Miles and the garrison, who had perhaps taken General McClellan\'s<br>instructions to hold the town at all costs too much to heart. On the evening of the 14th, several regiments from Jones\' brigade attempted a night assault to distract the Federals from the<br>flanking movement of A.P. Hill\'s brigade across the Shepherdstown Road and to the south of the Charlestown Pike.<br>They quickly scattered the few skirmishers arrayed below the entrenchments at Bolivar Heights, but were not able to get past the prominent ridgeline.<br>As A.P. Hill\'s Light Division got into position, the officers of the Union garrison were worriedly considering their situation in one of several counsels of war.<br>Colonel Miles doggedly refused his fellow officer\'s suggestions to leave the town or for an attempt to retake the Maryland Heights, possibly due to a stubborn and literal interpretation of his orders,<br>and possibly due to several allegations of being drunk during the siege. In either case, unbeknownst to the Federals, both sides were roughly equal in strength as over fifty guns from Schoolhouse Ridge,<br>Loudon Heights, and Maryland Heights ranged against the Union defenses and as the morning of the 15th dawned, a terrible bombardment was set to weaken their resolve...','Skirmish'),('ShenandoahStreet','Shenandoah Street','HarpersFerry','In this semi-fictitious scenario, AP Hill has broken past the southern defenses of Bolivar Heights, and is now threatening to take the downtown region of Harper\'s Ferry as blue-clad defenders scramble to stop the Confederates.','September 15th - 13:30','USA',110,124,104,'maps\\ShenandoahStreet_skirmish.png','maps\\ShenandoahStreet_spawn.png','maps\\ShenandoahStreet_loading.png',6,'Shenandoah Street went along the south side of the Harper\'s Ferry peninsula, following its namesake river. To the north of the road above the cliff faces were two of the town\'s most<br>prominent churches, including the St. Peter\'s Roman Catholic Church, and St. John\'s Episcopal Church, which were both overtaken as hospitals or barracks for the soldiers.<br>To the south, the road abuts the Upper and Lower Hall islands, and Virginius Island, which in the lead-up to the Civil War were heavily industrialized with various factories, worker housing, and mills.<br>When the Confederates were retreating from the town in 1861, these businesses were put to the flame once they had been fully looted just like the US Armory and the two bridges into town.<br>Another factor which made Harper\'s Ferry such a strategic town was the B&amp;O Railroad, the oldest railroad in the United States and a crucial supply route for Union forces all the way to<br>Chicago and the proverbial ‘breadbasket\' of the North. Colonel Miles had been in charge of protecting this important rail line prior to the Confederate invasion, where he and his troops<br>were diverted to protecting the town. Despite the burning of the original bridge across the Potomac in 1861, it took engineers from the B&amp;O company barely three weeks to rebuild a<br>metal truss-framed structure on the original foundations, which was guarded by two guns from Potts\' battery and the 1st Maryland Potomac Home Brigade during the siege.','Skirmish'),('Smokestacks','Smokestacks','Antietam','','',NULL,100,100,NULL,NULL,NULL,'maps\\Smokestacks_loading.png',0,NULL,'Conquest'),('ToweringTrunks','Towering Trunks','DrillCamp','','',NULL,100,100,NULL,NULL,NULL,'maps\\ToweringTrunks_loading.png',3,NULL,'Conquest'),('Valley','Valley','HarpersFerry','','',NULL,100,100,NULL,NULL,NULL,'maps\\Valley_loading.png',3,NULL,'Conquest'),('WashingtonStreet','Washington Street','HarpersFerry','In this fictitious scenario, the Union garrison attempt to defend against Confederates now streaming down Camp Hill by way of the main thoroughfare to Harper\'s Ferry from Bolivar – Washington Street.','September 15th - 15:30','USA',115,124,136,'maps\\WashingtonStreet_skirmish.png','maps\\WashingtonStreet_spawn.png','maps\\WashingtonStreet_loading.png',9,'After Colonel Miles and his fellow officers in blue considered their position, it was unanimously decided that they should surrender, Miles decided to ride to the Confederate lines<br>with a white handkerchief to submit their terms. However, as he rode toward the rebel lines a shell exploded near him and struck Miles in the leg, mortally wounding him.<br>Despite the strong Federal position on Bolivar Heights, with the almost uncontested surrounding of the peninsula their fate had been sealed. General Jackson was able to ride into the town and its valuable<br>stores of weapons, ammunition, uniforms, and food. Considering the General\'s dirty uniform, one Ohio private said to another that “He isn\'t much for looks, but if we\'d had him we wouldn\'t<br>have been caught in this trap.” As the Confederate forces for the second time took control of the town, Jackson received the urgent message from General Lee tasking him to return with all haste to the army at Sharpsburg.<br>Jackson left only A.P. Hill\'s division to finish the task of paroling the over 12,000 captured Union prisoners as his troops double-quicked to the north. Even though the siege had taken a<br>full day more than originally planned, Jackson had done admirably well in taking the town with minimal losses on either side besides the brief confrontation on the Maryland Heights.<br>For the Union forces that had been captured, they only had a few weeks to wait in a non-active duty role before being able to redeem themselves and their regiments in future engagements.<br>But Jackson\'s troops would soon see a more deadly elephant at Antietam in a few days time, and their relatively easy victory along the idyllic banks of the Potomac and Shenandoah<br>would soon be tempered by the full force of the Army of the Potomac then heading towards General Lee and the rest of the Army of Northern Virginia....','Skirmish'),('Waterways','Waterways','Antietam','','',NULL,100,100,NULL,NULL,NULL,'maps\\Waterways_loading.png',5,NULL,'Conquest'),('WestWoods','West Woods','Antietam','General Edwin Sumner\'s Union Second Corps advances into the West Woods where they are met by Confederate Wing Commander Jackson\'s men. Union General John Sedgwick\'s division is performing a series of reckless charges into the Confederates at very high costs to break the Confederate line.','September 17th - 10:00','CSA',137,110,152,'maps\\WestWoods_skirmish.png','maps\\WestWoods_spawn.png','maps\\WestWoods_loading.png',10,'Within an hour of their foray into the West Woods, Sedgwick was riddled with bullets in his wrist, leg, and shoulder,<br>and the units he led were almost completely halved as the division suffered over 2200 casualties.<br>General Sumner was forced to personally lead his shattered 2nd Division out of the West Woods and to the north<br>to escape the deadly fire of their Confederate rivals of Walker and McLaws brigades, who had just returned from the Siege of Harpers Ferry.<br>The remaining troops and guns of the I Corps helped prevent a complete slaughter or capture of Sedgwick\'s Division as they retreated back towards the Miller farm,<br>but neither of the exhausted sides were interested in continuing the fight in the northern part of the battlefield.<br>As the noonday sun crested in the sky, a fresh division under General Greene of Mansfield\'s XII Corps had arrived<br>through the East Woods to finish the work of their predecessors, and would soon feel the buzzing of shot and shell about them as the church loomed.<br>Despite taking elevated casualties due to deploying to the field initially in a column formation while in easy range of rebel guns, the Union troops ably pressed on.<br>They marched directly towards the particular guns of Captain Henry Carlton, which awaited the Yankees like a hungry maw...','Skirmish'),('WheatFields','Wheat Fields','SouthMountain','','',NULL,100,100,NULL,NULL,NULL,'maps\\WheatFields_loading.png',1,NULL,'Conquest');
